  "prompt": "Why do humans have allergies?",
  "response": "Allergies occur when the immune system overreacts to a typically harmless substance (allergen) by producing an immune response. There are several reasons why humans develop allergies:\n\n1. Genetic predisposition\n- Some people are more likely to develop allergies due to inherited genes\n- Family history of allergies increases the risk\n\n2. Immune system hypersensitivity\n- The immune system mistakenly identifies certain substances as harmful\n- It produces antibodies (IgE) to fight these perceived threats\n- This leads to inflammation and allergy symptoms\n\n3. Environmental factors\n- Increased exposure to potential allergens\n- Changes in environment and hygiene (hygiene hypothesis)\n- Reduced exposure to microbes during childhood may lead to increased allergies\n\n4. Evolutionary perspective\n- Allergic responses might have originally been a defense mechanism against parasites\n- In modern environments, this response can be triggered by harmless substances\n\n5. Modern lifestyle influences\n- Pollution\n- Dietary changes\n- Increased use of antibiotics\n- Reduced microbial diversity\n\nCommon allergens include pollen, dust mites, pet dander, certain foods, and medications. While allergies can be uncomfortable or even dangerous, they are the immune system's attempt to protect the body.",
